1.1 Importing HTML file

We can import the HTML file for the webpage by simply using read_html().

url <- 'http://books.toscrape.com/catalogue/category/books_1/index.html'
book_html <- read_html(url)

2 Scraping Books to Scrape

Now that we have the HTML file loaded into R, we can start to scrape some information from the webpage.

In class, you learned how to scrape using the xpath argument in html_elements(). Here, weâll use the css argument. Feel free to use whichever you prefer in your code.

2.1 Scraping Book Genres

First, letâs look into the book genres. Looking at the HTML document, it appears that all genres are held in a link that is contained in an element with class âside_categoriesâ. To get all the genres, we can start by looking for HTML elements with class âside_categoriesâ. Then, we look for link elements (i.e.Â âaâ elements) within âside_categoriesâ.

To retrieve elements of a certain class, we put a period in front of the class name, as shown below.

book_html %>%
  html_elements('.side_categories') %>%
  html_elements('a') %>%

2.2.4 Scraping Ratings

Finally, ratings are a bit more complex. The rating is encoded as a set of icons, but the class of that set of icons changes depending on the rating. For example, a five-star rating is contained in an element with class âstar-rating Fiveâ. Therefore, we need to scrape the class of the rating rather than the value of the element.

read_html(url) %>% 
  html_elements('p.star-rating') %>% 
  html_attr('class')
 [1] "star-rating Three" "star-rating One"   "star-rating One"  
 [4] "star-rating Four"  "star-rating Five"  "star-rating One"  
 [7] "star-rating Four"  "star-rating Three" "star-rating Four" 
[10] "star-rating One"   "star-rating Two"   "star-rating Four" 
[13] "star-rating Five"  "star-rating Five"  "star-rating Five" 
[16] "star-rating Three" "star-rating One"   "star-rating One"  
[19] "star-rating Two"   "star-rating Two"

However, we only want the last word of the above strings. We can use str_remove() to get ride of âstar-ratingâ in all our data.

read_html(url) %>% 
  html_elements('p.star-rating') %>% 
  html_attr('class') %>%
  str_remove('star-rating ')
 [1] "Three" "One"   "One"   "Four"  "Five"  "One"   "Four"  "Three" "Four" 
[10] "One"   "Two"   "Four"  "Five"  "Five"  "Five"  "Three" "One"   "One"  
[19] "Two"   "Two"

2.2.5 Data Frame for Scraped Data

We can put all of the data weâve scraped into a data frame to make it easier to work with.

title <- book_html %>% 
  html_elements('h3') %>%
  html_elements('a') %>%
  html_attr('title')

price <- book_html %>%
  html_elements('.price_color') %>%
  html_text2()

stock <- book_html %>%
  html_elements('.instock') %>%
  html_text2()

rating <- read_html(url) %>% 
  html_elements('p.star-rating') %>% 
  html_attr('class') %>%
  str_remove('star-rating ')

book_info <- data.frame(
  Title = title,
  Price = price,
  Stock = stock,
  Rating = rating
)
